{"id":"1104.1171","submitter":"Pradeep Sarvepalli","authors":"Pradeep Sarvepalli","title":"Quantum Codes and Symplectic Matroids","comments":"LateX, 7 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The correspondence between linear codes and representable matroids is well\nknown. But a similar correspondence between quantum codes and matroids is not\nknown. We show that representable symplectic matroids over a finite field\n$\\mathbb{F}_q$ correspond to $\\mathbb{F}_q$-linear quantum codes. Although this\nconnection is straightforward, it does not appear to have been made earlier in\nliterature. The correspondence is made through isotropic subspaces. We also\nshow that the popular Calderbank-Shor-Steane (CSS) codes are essentially the\nhomogenous symplectic matroids while the graph states, which figure so\nprominently in measurement based quantum computation, correspond to a special\nclass of symplectic matroids, namely Lagrangian matroids. This association is\nuseful in that it enables the study of symplectic matroids in terms of quantum\ncodes and vice versa. Furthermore, it has application in the study of quantum\nsecret sharing schemes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 6 Apr 2011 19:41:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-04-07"}
